Description

The manipal_train dataset provides information customer satisfaction by patients of Manipal Hospital. The hospital management collected an tabulated scores on multiple parameters on a Likert scale type feedback and on the basis of the same categorised the respondents as “Promotors” or Detractors”.

Objective and Approach

Manipal Hospital seeks to use its past data to identify Detractors amonst its future patients. The analyst is tasked to use the manipal_train data to train multiple Supervised Learning models and make predictions on the manipal_test data. The approaches deployed as part of analysis are :

  1. Logistic Regression (Including Stepwise and Over-Sampled Models)
  2. Decision Tree
  3. Random Forest
  4. Support Vector Machines(Linear and Radial Models)

Creating copies of the train and test datasets for further analysis

train <- manipal_train

test <- manipal_test

Cleaning & Preparing the Dataset for Analysis

Deleting variables that would not be considered for the analysis. These variables contain serial and identification numbers, geographical information and dates of stay.

train <- train[ , -c(1,2,10:12,48,49)]
test <- test[ , -c(1,2,10:12,48,49)]

The Likert scale CSAT scores are being read as numeric. Transforming the same to be ordered factors.

numeric <- c("CE_ACCESSIBILITY", "CE_CSAT", "CE_VALUEFORMONEY", "EM_IMMEDIATEATTENTION",  "EM_NURSING",
             "EM_DOCTOR", "EM_OVERALL", "AD_TIME", "AD_TARRIFFPACKAGESEXPLAINATION", "AD_STAFFATTITUDE",
             "INR_ROOMCLEANLINESS", "INR_ROOMPEACE", "INR_ROOMEQUIPMENT", "INR_ROOMAMBIENCE", 
             "FNB_FOODQUALITY", "FNB_FOODDELIVERYTIME", "FNB_DIETICIAN",  "FNB_STAFFATTITUDE", 
             "AE_ATTENDEECARE", "AE_PATIENTSTATUSINFO", "AE_ATTENDEEFOOD", "DOC_TREATMENTEXPLAINATION",
             "DOC_ATTITUDE",  "DOC_VISITS", "DOC_TREATMENTEFFECTIVENESS", "NS_CALLBELLRESPONSE",
             "NS_NURSESATTITUDE", "NS_NURSEPROACTIVENESS", "NS_NURSEPATIENCE", "OVS_OVERALLSTAFFATTITUDE",
             "OVS_OVERALLSTAFFPROMPTNESS", "OVS_SECURITYATTITUDE", "DP_DISCHARGETIME","DP_DISCHARGEQUERIES",              "DP_DISCHARGEPROCESS")

train[numeric] <- lapply(train[numeric], factor, levels= c("4","3","2","1"), 
                         labels = c("Not at all Satisfied", "Less Satisfied",
                                    "Mostly Satisfied","Extremely Satisfied"),
                         ordered = TRUE) 

test[numeric] <- lapply(test[numeric], factor, levels= c("4","3","2","1"), 
                        labels = c("Not at all Satisfied", "Less Satisfied",
                                   "Mostly Satisfied","Extremely Satisfied"),
                        ordered = TRUE)

Transforming the character variables to factors

train <- as.data.frame(unclass(train), stringsAsFactors = T)
test <- as.data.frame(unclass(test), stringsAsFactors = T)

Defining the target variable as Yes and No based on the NPS_Status and converting the same to factor

train$Detractor <- ifelse(train$NPS_Status == "Detractor", "Yes","No")
test$Detractor <- ifelse(test$NPS_Status == "Detractor", "Yes","No")

train$Detractor <- as.factor(train$Detractor)
test$Detractor <- as.factor(test$Detractor)

Checking the correlation between CE_NPS and NPS_Status variables

train %>% filter(NPS_Status == "Detractor") %>% summarise(max(CE_NPS))
##   max(CE_NPS)
## 1           8
chisq.test(train$NPS_Status, train$CE_NPS)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  train$NPS_Status and train$CE_NPS
## X-squared = 4989, df = 10, p-value < 2.2e-16

There is high correlation between CE_NPS and NPS_Status. Observations with score of 8 and below are categorized as Detractors and over 8 are Promoters. Dropping the CE_NPS and NPS_Status variables from train data.

Making predictions with the model on the test data

“pred <- predict(lr_mdl1, newdata = test, type =”response”)”

“Error in model.frame.default(Terms, newdata, na.action = na.action, xlev = object$xlevels) : factor NS_NURSEPROACTIVENESS has new levels Extremely Satisfied”

summary(train$NS_NURSEPROACTIVENESS)

##                 3459                 1408                  122 
##  Extremely Satisfied 
##                    0
summary(test$NS_NURSEPROACTIVENESS)
## Not at all Satisfied       Less Satisfied     Mostly Satisfied 
##                  212                  129                   19 
##  Extremely Satisfied 
##                    4

There are 4 obesations in the NS_NURSEPROACTIVENESS variable in the “Extremely Satisfied” level of the test data but 0 in the train data. Dropping those 4 obersations and attempting to fit the model.

test <- test[!(test$NS_NURSEPROACTIVENESS == "Extremely Satisfied"), ]

pred <- predict(lr_mdl1, newdata = test, type = "response")

test$lr_pred <- ifelse(pred >= 0.5, "Detractor", "Promotor")

test$lr_pred <- as.factor(test$lr_pred)

Traing a Linear and Radial SVM Models for Binomial Classification

Balancing the train data

train2 <- manipal_train

train2 <- train2[ , -c(1,2,10:12,48,49)]

train2[numeric] <- lapply(train2[numeric], factor) 

train2 <- as.data.frame(unclass(train2), stringsAsFactors = T)

train2$Detractor <- ifelse(train2$NPS_Status == "Detractor", "Yes","No")

train2$Detractor <- as.factor(train2$Detractor)

train2 <- train2[ , -c(44, 45)]

t2_numeric <- sapply(train2, is.numeric)

t2_integer <- sapply(train2, is.integer)

t2_factor <- sapply (train2, is.factor)

df1 <- t2_numeric | t2_integer

df2 <- scale(train2[, df1])

df3 <- train2[, t2_factor]

train2_scaled <- data.frame(df2, df3)

train_bal <- ROSE(Detractor ~ ., data = train2_scaled, seed = 2205)$data

train_bal[numeric] <- lapply(train_bal[numeric], factor, levels= c("4","3","2","1"), 
                             labels = c("Not at all Satisfied", "Less Satisfied",
                                        "Mostly Satisfied","Extremely Satisfied"),
                             ordered = TRUE) 

table(train_bal$Detractor)
## 
##   No  Yes 
## 2500 2489

Transforming the test data to match the balanced train data

test3 <- manipal_test

test3 <- test3[ , -c(1,2,10:12,48,49)]

test3[numeric] <- lapply(test3[numeric], factor) 

test3 <- as.data.frame(unclass(test3), stringsAsFactors = T)

test3$Detractor <- ifelse(test3$NPS_Status == "Detractor", "Yes","No")
test3$Detractor <- as.factor(test3$Detractor)

t3_numeric <- sapply(test3, is.numeric)

t3_integer <- sapply(test3, is.integer)

t3_factor <- sapply(test3, is.factor)

df_t3 <- t3_numeric | t3_integer

df_test3 <- scale(test3[, df_t3])

df2_test3 <- test3[, t3_factor]

test_scaled <- data.frame(df_test3, df2_test3)

test_scaled[numeric] <- lapply(test_scaled[numeric], factor, levels= c("4","3","2","1"), 
                               labels = c("Not at all Satisfied", "Less Satisfied",
                                          "Mostly Satisfied","Extremely Satisfied"),
                               ordered = TRUE) 

test_scaled <- test_scaled[!(test_scaled$NS_NURSEPROACTIVENESS == "Extremely Satisfied"), ]

Building a SVM Model based on Linear Kernel

Grid search for Linear Kernel

set.seed (2205)

trControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", 
                          number = 10)

Define the tuning grid

tuneGrid <- expand.grid(C = c(0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10))

Training the linear model

set.seed(2205)

linear_model <- train(Detractor ~ ., 
                      data = train_bal, 
                      method = "svmLinear",
                      trControl = trControl,
                      tuneGrid = tuneGrid)

print(linear_model)

Model Comparison

model_comparison <- data.frame(Model = c("Logistic Regression", "Step-wise Logistic Regression", 
                                         "Over-Sampled Logistic Regression", "Decision Tree", 
                                         "Pruned Decision Tree", "Random Forest", "Linear Kernel SVM",
                                         "Radial Kernel SVM"), 
Accuracy = c(0.68,  0.70, 0.66, 0.65, 0.71, 0.73, 0.66, 0.56), 
Sensitivity = c(0.51, 0.51, 0.60, 0.59, 0.58, 0.60, 0.59, 0.87), 
Specificity = c(0.82, 0.84, 0.70, 0.70, 0.81, 0.84, 0.71, 0.32))

model_comparison
##                              Model Accuracy Sensitivity Specificity
## 1              Logistic Regression     0.68        0.51        0.82
## 2    Step-wise Logistic Regression     0.70        0.51        0.84
## 3 Over-Sampled Logistic Regression     0.66        0.60        0.70
## 4                    Decision Tree     0.65        0.59        0.70
## 5             Pruned Decision Tree     0.71        0.58        0.81
## 6                    Random Forest     0.73        0.60        0.84
## 7                Linear Kernel SVM     0.66        0.59        0.71
## 8                Radial Kernel SVM     0.56        0.87        0.32

As Manipal Hospital is seeking accurate identification and prediction of Detractors, the Radial Kernel SVM offers the highest Sensitivity at 87%. The model however, performs poorly on overall accuracy and Specificity. Depending on the organization decision to trade-off on Sensitivity for better accuracy and specificity, the Random Forest Model can be used for Detractor prediction as it offers a 73% accuracy with 60% Sensitivity and 84% Specificity.
